            while (low <= high) {
                int mid = (high - low) / 2 + low;
                if (numbers[mid] +numbers[i] == target)
                    return new int[]{i + 1, mid + 1};
                else if (numbers[mid] + numbers[i] > target) 
                    high = mid - 1;
                else 
                    low = mid + 1;
            }
        }
        return new int[]{-1, -1};
    }
}
```
**HashMap Approach**
**Logic**
We define a HashMap and then check whether the sum is available in the array or not by travesing through the sorted array

**Complexity**
TC - O(n)
SC - O(n)

**Code  -->**
class Solution {
    public int[] twoSum(int[] numbers, int target) {

        int len = numbers.length;
        Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
            if (map.containsKey(target - numbers[i])) 
                return new int[]{map.get(target - numbers[i]), i + 1};
            map.putIfAbsent(numbers[i], i + 1);
        }
        return new int[0];
    }
}

**BruteForce Approach**
**Logic**
We iterate through two loops and check whether the summation of ith element and jth element is equal to the target or not

**Complexity**
TC - O(n^2)
SC - O(1)

