# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
It is similar to a leetcode problem number 1, where array is not sorted. Here, we are given sorted array which make easy for finding optimal solution. 

# Approach Number 2 (Iterative) 
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
**similar to Two sum problem - leetcode problem 1**
1. Run loop from i = 0 to size-1 and another loop(nested one) j = i+1 to size-1.
2. check if(nums[i] + nums[j] == target), return {i+1,j+1};

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->O(N^2)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->O(1)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++)
        for(int j = i+1; j < nums.size(); j++)
        if(nums[i]+nums[j]==target)
        return {i+1,j+1};
        return {};
    }
};
```
# OPTIMIZATION:-O(n^2)-> O(N).
# Approach Number 2
1. set two pointer i = 0 and j =  size-1.
2. Iterative till (i < j)
3. At each step do the following,
- if(nums[i] + nums[j] == target), return {i+1,j+1};
- else if(nums[i] + nums[j] > target), means our sum is greater than target, (2+15=17>9), we need a smaller number to reduce the sum, so decrease j by 1 as array is sorted.
- else increase i by 1. means our sum is smaller thsn target, (2+5=7 9), we need a greater number to increase the sum, so increase i by 1 as array is sorted.

# Complexity.
**Time**-O(N)
**Space**-O(1)

